Comment::::<div class="com_user_text">
                            All welfare states of the world focus on three issues for the wellbeing of the people : health, education and promoting small businesses. So this govt isnt too far off the mark when its targetting these areas for the betterment of aam aadmi's life.<br/><br/>
But the AAP govt will do well to remember that While the NHS model has several positives worth emulating it is also an expensive model. This year's NHS budget is GBP 115billion. Compare that to the current year's budgetary expenditure of the indian govt at about GBP 56billion.And also worth remembering NHS services a population of only 65 million with that budget.<br/><br/>
Doctors working for NHS meet no more than 5-8 patients in a day. Indian doctors sometimes meet as many as 80 patients in a day. <br/><br/>
Personally I believe the practices from NHS that can be emulated at an affordable cost have to do with the heavily networked knowledge database that they have created. Not only does it maintain patient treatment histories and test reports, the knowledge base also has standardized diagnostic and treatment methodologies for common ailments that medical practitioners are expected to follow. <br/><br/>
UK also has laws that holds NHS doctors accountable in case of medical negligence. So the NHS system is built to not only to support the medical fraternity but to also challenge if good practices arent followed. The system also relies on good quality training and accredition practices for medical professionals.
